inn1.comm: off the mark straight away, that's massive, a poke to the covers, a dash to the other end and a huge stare from McGrath. Welcome
pushed right up there, on the money, and that's defended down by Porterhouse
short, a mistimed pull to square and the call immediately comes: "Wait!"
angled across the lefthander, scrambled seam, testing him outside off and he just lets that go. Good ball from Glenn
slower ball, poked down and they set off. They have to hurry... or they would have done if Mr Mike Hussey-Cricket hadn't fumbled on his way through
and that's a very early strike indeed, inswing clipped the outside of off stump. Bray didn't move his feet, tried to jab down on it. Failed
quick and hostile immediately - just shooting that past the outside edge, rearing up and past the head. Gilchrist likes that one
left alone outside off stump
full toss at the hips and that's just skewed into the covers. Full tosses are usually gifts, but their angle can be quite awkward
on middle, short and there's some excitement as that's tucked down to the man at square
more of the sharp stuff, that one outside off, on a yorker length and the batsman played very late indeed - that ball was too quick for him
low full toss on leg and that's too quick for him, just crashing into his knee roll, but would have gone on past leg
brings his bat down on that one, which was full and pitched just in front of him on line with off
pushed right up there and that's played down into the covers
left alone outside off as that slinks through on a good length
that one cut back in, just a touch, at the lefthander - plenty of bounce again and nearly cutting him up
well struck by Morgan in front of point, but Symonds stops that in the covers
up there, on leg, and that's pushed to square
right up there, straight, on leg, not much swing, too quick for the batsman and not much time's needed for the decision
...and out again: full toss, and there's no footwork as the batsman drags a huge inside edge back onto his stumps and Tait's on a hat-trick
ooh, as close as you can get to a hat-trick without getting a hat-trick - too good that one, squaring him up at 92mph, and it just slinks past his outside edge - just
down leg, Tait must think he's still bowling to lefthanders
more of the leg stuff, this one rising a bit more, hopping over O'Brien's bent back
just too short, but straight, and that's played well off the toes through midwicket
short, the batsman ducks into it, right into it, and that clatters right into his bat. He didn't flinch
a good shot again, tucked off the toes again and that races again
left alone outside off
short, played into the covers and will they run? "No!" I like a good, clear call like that
very soft, on off stump, and that's outside-edged to first slip. Ireland in complete disarray
driven into the covers
stands tall, and that's an inside edge, nearly back on the stumps, but not quite and Gilchrist tidies
pushed into the covers
outside off, some naughty swing threatens to send back yet another Irish player, but he doesn't connect with a loose swish away from his body, his feet stuck in the ground
misdirected sling shot at 90mph (145kph) down off (Warp factor 0.2 for any Klingons out there)
another wide, this one down leg at 91.6mph, which is 145.5kph, warp factor 0.202. 1612.16 inches a second
outside off, and left alone
defended forward tis time
another wide down leg, at 92mph, spot on 148kph
dropped! Ponting dives to his right to take a relatively difficult chance at second slip, the ball popping out of his hands as he lands
oh dear
is Tait being greedy or what? This time he sprays the ball wide down off
again drifting on the pads and neatly clipped away through square leg, it pulls up short of the rope
almost as slow as a spinner after Tait's onslaught - a sedate 80mph - outside off and left alone
steered round the corner, not controlled, extra bounce surprised him a little and he withdrew his bottom hand off the bat as he played the stroke
pushed to mid-on
pushed to point with a loud shout of "no"
patted back to McGrath who ambles down the track to field, before turning and lolloping back to his mark
short, outside off, White tries an expansive pull and misses. McGrath smiles a kind of "I'll get you next over" smile
Clarke continues where his team-mate left off with a leg-side wide
O'Brien shuffles across the crease and it smacked on the pads, not forward, and a loud shout ... close but just going over the top
squirted out to midwicket
good line, on off stump at 80mph, O'Brien behind the ball to block
just short of a length outside off, O'Brien swishes with minimal footwork and misses ... all the close fielders ooh and aah as Gilchrist takes the ball
O'Brien blocks a ball on the spot
Clarke in a good rhythm now and O'Brien happy to defend
left alone outside off, taking his bat away from it and standing firm on the back foot
in that corridor where nothing's certain again, but the batsman is firm in his decision to leave it, at least
nips back in off the seam and that's left alone
outside off and that's driven through the covers
left alone outside off again
nasty, oh dear, White ducked straight into that bouncer and it makes a sickening blow as it clatters into his helmet
chases that down leg
stands tall and defends that down off the backfoot, more of the solid stuff
right up there on a good length and that's defended forward
outside off and that's firmly driven straight to cover
outside off and found the gap this time with a firm cover drive to bring up Ireland's 30, which is roundly clapped
defended off the back foot
no sign of any discomfort after being smacked on the cranium in the previous over; a lovely flick off his legs, albeit a full toss on leg stump, neatly timed through midwicket
just short of a length, lacking any pace and White is back and across, pushing it out to cover
great catch! An excellent slower ball which he misread, spooning it over McGrath's head; Hogg sprints to his right and takes a fine, low catch
a short bouncer, wild and wooly and down the leg side
just outside off and he leaves it alone
that'll make him feel better, a firm, crunching late cut down to third man
on middle-and-leg, he's right back in his stumps - practically sitting on his stumps - and defends off the back foot
too short and straight, clipped off his legs but straight to midwicket
ooh luverly yorker from Clark there, on off stump and swinging into the batsman who digs it out with his willow spade
easily nudged to leg for a single
play and a miss outside off. That kept disconcertingly low on O'Brien who fished at it, missed it and they all go home for tea
but a touch of bounce there from Clark, outside off, O'Brien cuts hard but can only find thin air. An almighty heave ho.
solidly, firmly cut off the back foot past point
shot! That's a delicious shot, timing a fairly meek delivery on his legs, punching it with pleasing timing past mid-on
that's more like it from the old man; just outside off and it's clamped down upon by the batsman
shot - but brilliantly fielded by Clarke at backward point. It was savagely cut just to Clarke's right who dived and saved four
short of a length and left alone
calmly driven, if a little uppishly, through the covers without really timing it...but neatly placed nevertheless
ooh edged but just short of first slip. Some way short of the slips in fact
drifting onto his pads and timed beautifully, with an elegant flick of his wrists, but he picks out Hodge at short midwicket who didn't need move an inch, taking the ball at head height
ah, lovely bowling; spearing in to his leg stump like a stray missile, squeezed out by the batsman
too short and it's uppercut down to McGrath at third man - who makes a complete hash of it. He only had a few yards to run to his right, but seemed to give up at the last moment
firmly pushed back to the bowler
excellent ball on middle-and-off and it's defended solidly on the front foot
a roar from Tait, as is his wont, but it's short and wide enough to be left alone with ease
tighter length and a touch fuller, left alone at the last moment
very nicely played, just calmly driving this on the front foot through the infield, past cover, for a couple
flicked off his legs to Hodge who, rather impetuously, shies at the stumps but hits the batsman
an ugly, short, wide, lifting delivery which is easily left alone
oh nearly goddim there. A fearsome ball just outside off, full and fast which is clamped down upon at the very last moment, gets a bottom edge, and the ball very nearly shaves his off stump
but that's much better from McCallan, confidently (ish) forward and defended with a straight bat
pushed easily to cover, but straight to cover
an attempted bouncer? Perhaps not quite short enough to be considered a bouncer, but nevertheless he shies away from it, dropping his hands low
and another one which keeps low, rattling into his pads
ooh close! A play-and-a-miss outside off to a really fine leg-cutter, swinging further away after cutting
onto the front foot and he tries to clobber it but can only clatter it straight into the ground
well played. A full toss worked off his legs, past the diving short midwicket; the Hogg runs around from deep square leg, tongue slavering out of his mouth like a Labrador
rubbish. Short, wide and wided by the umpire

much, much better, angling into the batsman and it actually holds its line there. Perhaps the batsman was expecting it to swing, or cut, away, as indicated by his attempt to hammer it off the back foot. And he missed
my word that was sharp; on middle stump, he tries to nudge it to leg but appears to get a thin edge which the slips, wicketkeeper and bowler all appeal for. Perhaps it brushed his pad

but he's got him this time. Clever bowling from Tait, sending it just a touch wider and enticing the drive. Johnston goes for an expansive slap through the covers, but instead the ball slaps into his stumps
excellent first nut, on leg stump, but it's squeezed out on the back foot, square of the wicket out into the off side
on off stump, swinging back into the left hander who jumps back to leg, as though shocked by an electric pokery implement, and pushes i to leg
neatly driven down the ground
a classic Clark cutter, and a fine piece of alliteration there from Will, as this little off cutter just moves away from a tentative forward defence from the batsman
ever-so-slightly shorter, allowing him just a fraction more time to read the length and it's left alone. Wisely. Like an owl.
a nothing delivery, really, too wide of the off stump to threaten the batsman
short and wide, once again, and left alone
short, rising onto the left hander who punches it off the back foot to cover
forward on the front foot, if not quite to the pitch of the ball, and it's sliced to point
ooh that was quick. 92 mph, but looked faster, and swinging into the batsman who dug it out
nicely clunked to extra cover, and they set off for a single
well that's vicious, if wooly - not to mention wild. Short, and he ducks underneath it
much better; full, swinging into the left hander's off stump who somehow gets bat on it, inside-edging it onto his boot but fortunately not onto his pads
terrific stop from Symonds at extra cover saves four. Mooney just pushed at it, seemingly without any power, but such is Tait's pace that it fairly sped off the bat
shot! That's what he was attempting the previous delivery, driving this on the up past Symonds this time. Fabulous shot
pushed out off the back foot and he screams through for a single
on off stump, he tries to paddle it but misses
nearly! On middle-and-off, he came forward meekly and tried to defend it but the spin of the ball almost saw it wobble into his stumps
pushed out to cover for a single
smothered by the batsman on the front foot
the wrong'un which is misread by the batsman who plays and misses outside off
swept just behind square
here comes Symonds, chugging in, and it's defended on the front foot
good length, if slightly wide, and it's defended out to cover
too straight but he can't make anything of it, nudging it to leg and straight to midwicket
just a little too wide, but it's a good length from Symonds here, not allowing the batsman to drive
but he does drive this time, though it's a little short to be doing so and it's aerially clubbed to cover
gone this time. McCallan was getting fed up with all this poking and prodding; a cemented front foot, a swing of the bat, the ball ballooning to mid-on who took a simple catch to his right
turning back into the right hander who defends off the back foot
on leg stump, turned to short fine leg. Oh dear, it's Symonds there and they take him on - with a single, not in terms of asking him for a fight or anything - but his throw is wide
big shout by Gilchrist to one he padded away
pushed out to cover on the front foot
on off stump and pushed calmly back to the bowler
short and wide but he misses out, playing and missing.
ooh nicely bowled, shaping back into the batsman but he played it quite competently; coming forward and angling it down to third man
very well bowled - a fuller length this time which is defended, or rather dug out
edged, but it doesn't carry, falling just short of the colossus that is Hayden at first slip
crashed into the covers but he can't bisect it
a play and a miss outside off - well bowled
and he does get an edge this time, but it's wide of the lone slip
Dave's gone! Stepping back, not picking it at all, he tries to defend but it takes the outside edge, ballooning to Ricky Ponting at silly point
huge appeal - a quicker one which raps him on the pad. And that looks absolutely dead, but Rudi doesn't like it
forward come Rankin, playing it with impressively soft hands (perhaps I'm being overly generous there), to one just falling short of slip
solidly defended this time
drifting down the leg side
terrific ball, the wrong'un, not picked by Rankin who plays and misses
pushed out to leg
firmly punched on the front foot, square of the wicket
and it's left alone outside off. Just a hint of away movement there
just a bit of wobble back into the left hander who is cautiously forward, poking it out to cover
well that's a belting delivery from Symonds, an inducker which completely beats Rankin
a tighter line this time which Rankin blocks out on the front foot
a swing, a miss, and Rankin survives
poked down off the back foot
left alone outside off
turns into the lefthander and there's a cry of "Catch" as he plays it down towards square
another premature "Catch!" for one which is cut down to gully
hits him outside off and he's sweeping - that doesn't stop the shouts of "Howzat", though, vain as they are
ooh, rushes that one past the outside edge, the batsman cuts under it and Mark Nicholas believes that's "Great fun" to watch
right on the money immediately and that's left alone outside off

extraordinary stuff. The batsman nearly gets an own goal by nodding the ball back onto the sticks; it rushes straight down and nurdles just past. Ponting picks up the ricochet and tries to shy down the non-striker's end
a direct hit, again, would have had them in trouble, this time from Hussey at mid-off, but he misses and there are overthrows
left alone outside off
outside off, the batsman just prods behind his leg, getting right inside the line of the ball
straight and that's outside edged - almost controlled - down to GD at third man, but they decide not to take the run for striker reasons
outside off and that's rushed through, Brad and his tongue liking that one
worked off the toes round down to fine leg and they scamper through two
"How?" they cry but zat's missing leg stump - great flipper, nevertheless, pushing the batsman back, skidding on quickly
a hoick and a miss - trying to slash from outside off to leg
played down to gully
chased that down leg, but it's wide all the same
driven out to long-off
prodded into short midwicket
right up there, straight as you like
driven to cover
driven through cover but there's a straight throw which comes back in just over the stumps, nice work
driven back to the bowler
slower ball, a touch short and that's driven out in front of midwicket for two. Clap up the 90, etc
driven into the covers and that's picked up tidily enough
pushed onto the back foot
Rudi Koertzen's a kidder. That one's curved past the outside edge, Gilchrist thinks it's out and the umpire shapes to give it so, but decides he's just moving his left arm. Gilchrist can't believe it
genuine edge, falling short of Hayden at first slip
turned round to short fine leg
driven to mid-off and Tait shies down the stumps on the bounce; that's well out

inn2.comm: brilliant ball to a righthander, as that one swings away down the leg-side and is called wide
full toss, thigh-height, and that's driven firmly back to mid-on
very good effort to keep that in on the midwicket boundary by McCallan, at full stretch
more diving efforts inside the rope, this time by Bray at third man, that one just pushed with an open face down on
vicious late swing, after it had gone past the bat
driven into the leg-side ring and that's a quick single
driven into the ground through cover, who gets a fingertip on it
gets some bounce and that's defended off the back foot
on leg and that's poked to short midwicket
straight, shooting up and it's shot down off the back foot, defensively, into the leg side - the pair look for a single, but decide not to go for it
oh, a tester, nipping off the seam on a good length
leg-side wide, trying to bounce Hussey - got the angle and line all wrong, though
on leg, and that's tucked without much fuss into the leg-side
on leg, going for the bouncer again, not getting it, and that was turned round to deep fine leg... ah, make that long leg, then
straight, short and played defensively down off the back foot
swinging down leg, too wide
driven out to long-on
four leg byes off the thigh
swished at that one outside off
Dave nearly gets a wicket there, Gilchrist chopping that one back towards the stumps with an inside edge
swings away from the lefthander and on and on
short, on leg, and that's tucked into short midwicket
chased that down leg
outside off and that's left alone
that one strays down leg
on leg and that's just tucked down to square
poor direction again, and there was just a touch of bat involved
outside off and there's enough room and time for the batsman to stand up on his back foot and play that out to third man
worked into the leg side
punched into the leg side off the front foot
round the wicket, Gilchrist nicks that out to Boyd Rankin at, appropriately enough, long leg and he does well to keep that inside the rope
swinging back into him, but that's dispatched with a forceful cover drive and that's travelling
width outside off and that gets the treatment, attempted slower ball, and that's lashed again through cover drive
width again, Gilchrist steps out to it and smashes it off the back foot through point
over the wicket, up there, and that's defended forward
pushed up there and that's defended down tidily
on leg, a touch short and that's tucked off the hips
misdirected down leg, lots of swing and that's well taken by O'Brien behind the stumps. well, nearly at leg slip in fact
tries to pull, but doesn't get hold of it
well bowled, just outside off, and that swings back into him
swings back into the lefthander from outside off
chases that round and the keeper appeals
timed well in front of midwicket
short and tries to rush that up, and ultimately down, to fine leg
horrible from Johnston, full toss outside off, and Hussey leans into a cover drive
turned it round through fine leg and that races away
short and that's driven out to short midwicket
short, on leg, and that's hooked round to wide long leg
on a good length, and that's defended down
punches straight through long-off
oh, Rankin thought he had Gilchrist then, there was a loud woody click, but it was the bat crunching down on the ball, skewing an edge into his leg
outside off and that's driven straight back past the bowler
plays away from his body, there's an inside edge but that doesn't carry through to the keeper and Gilchrist gets away with it
swing again, on his toes, and that's worked away to fine leg
swing again, and on a good length, and that's just defended on the front foot
swing down the channel, on a good length, and that's left alone
outside off, pushed up there, but the batsman drives into the covers
done him! Great ball from Johnston, nipping back in off the seam at the lefthander, keeping low, the stumps go flying and the bowler does a jig
off the mark straight away with a drive to mid-on
on the spot, and that's defended down
short and that's thumped through midwicket with a powerful pull shot
outside off and that's dabbed out to third man
dropped! Bray got two hands to that one, but it was travelling, a real rocket of a flat-bat swipe outside off
defended forward
a Symonds special. Steps down the track and just lifts a half-volley straight and over the boundary boards
wide down off and that's left alone
outside off and Hussey shoulders his shoulders
nips back in off the seam, but that's overstepped by Johnston
nips back in and there's some swing, too
he's bowling round the wicket, by the way, and that's defended into the covers
ooh, outside off, crunched to the covers and a direct hit would have had Symonds in some difficulty
squares him up a touch and that's outside edged down in front of the slips
lost his radar there, and that one's skewed down leg
turned away behind square
on the money and that's defended quietly forward
on a good spot again and that's defended forward
just outside off and that's defended into the covers
Hussey knows it, too, and he's driven that aerially in front of midwicket
outside off and that's dabbed to gully
turning over towards leg and that's poked to midwicket
outside off, up there, and that's defended forward
outside off and that's planted right over midwicket to end the match
